{
  "text": "While FMs are permissive to viral infections, including influenza virus [CITATION_1] (Uchide et al., , b, 2006 [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , CMV [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] , and herpes virus [CITATION_7] , and viral infections can trigger an inflammatory cytokine response in the chorioamnion [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] , little is known about the mechanisms involved. One way in which infection-associated inflammation at the maternal -fetal interface arises is through activation of the innate immune Toll-like receptors (TLRs) [CITATION_11] . We have previously shown that normal human FMs at term constitutively express TLRs 1-10, as well as the two major TLR adapter proteins, MyD88 and TRIF [CITATION_12] . Moreover, in response to bacterial agonists, TLR2, TLR4, TLR5 and TLR9 mediate distinct FM cytokine profiles [CITATION_13] . Thus, we hypothesized that this might also be the case for TLR3, which senses viral dsRNA and TLR8, which detects viral ssRNA [CITATION_14] . Therefore, the objective of this study was to characterize the cytokine profile and antiviral response in human FMs exposed to the viral signatures, dsRNA and ssRNA, and to determine the mechanisms involved.",
  "correct_citation": {
